<div class="panel" data-panel="calories">
  <div class="ref-panel">
    <div class="ref-header">
      <h2>Calorie & Macro Calculator</h2>
      <p>Evidence-based calorie and macronutrient targets using the Mifflin-St Jeor equation — the most validated formula for RMR estimation. Results are educational estimates. Refer detailed meal planning to a Registered Dietitian (RD).</p>
    </div>

    <div class="calc-wrap">
      <h3>Client Profile</h3>
      <div class="calc-grid">
        <div class="calc-field"><label>Sex</label><select id="c-sex"><option value="m">Male</option><option value="f">Female</option></select></div>
        <div class="calc-field"><label>Age (years)</label><input type="number" id="c-age" placeholder="35" min="16" max="100"></div>
        <div class="calc-field"><label>Height (inches)</label><input type="number" id="c-height" placeholder="68" min="48" max="96"></div>
        <div class="calc-field"><label>Weight (lbs)</label><input type="number" id="c-weight" placeholder="175" min="80" max="500"></div>
        <div class="calc-field"><label>Activity Level</label>
          <select id="c-activity">
            <option value="1.2">Sedentary (desk job, no exercise)</option>
            <option value="1.375">Lightly active (1–3 days/week)</option>
            <option value="1.55" selected>Moderately active (3–5 days/week)</option>
            <option value="1.725">Very active (6–7 days/week)</option>
            <option value="1.9">Extremely active (2× daily training)</option>
          </select>
        </div>
        <div class="calc-field"><label>Primary Goal</label>
          <select id="c-goal">
            <option value="loss">Fat Loss</option>
            <option value="maintain">Maintenance / Recomp</option>
            <option value="gain">Muscle Gain</option>
            <option value="glp1">GLP-1/AOM Client</option>
          </select>
        </div>
      </div>
      <button class="calc-btn" onclick="calcCalories()">Calculate Targets</button>

      <div class="calc-results" id="calcResults">
        <h4>Results</h4>
        <div class="result-cards" id="resultCards"></div>
        <div class="goal-tabs" id="goalTabs"></div>
        <h4 id="macroLabel">Daily Macros</h4>
        <div class="macro-row" id="macroRow"></div>
        <div id="calcNotes" class="calc-note"></div>
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="accord">
      <button class="accord-hdr open" onclick="tog(this)">How to Use These Numbers with Clients <svg width="16" height="16" viewBox="0 0 24 24" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2"><polyline points="6 9 12 15 18 9"/></svg></button>
      <div class="accord-body open">
        <span class="sub-lbl">Trainer's Role vs. RD's Role</span>
        Trainers provide <strong>general nutrition education</strong> — calorie awareness, protein priority, hydration. They do not prescribe meal plans, diagnose deficiencies, or provide therapeutic diets. Refer to a Registered Dietitian for clinical nutrition work.
        <span class="sub-lbl">Practical Coaching Points</span>
        <ul>
          <li>Use the number to <strong>educate, not prescribe</strong> — "Research suggests someone your size and activity level needs approximately X calories"</li>
          <li>Always emphasize <strong>protein first</strong> — it's the most impactful single variable for body composition</li>
          <li>Remind clients that calculators estimate TDEE based on averages — individual variance is ±10–15%</li>
          <li>For GLP-1 clients: appetite suppression often drives intake well below targets — protein shakes are frequently necessary to hit minimums</li>
          <li>For older adults: protein distribution (30–40g per meal) matters as much as total protein</li>
        </ul>
        <span class="sub-lbl">Mifflin-St Jeor Formula</span>
        Men: RMR = (10 × kg) + (6.25 × cm) − (5 × age) + 5<br>
        Women: RMR = (10 × kg) + (6.25 × cm) − (5 × age) − 161<br>
        TDEE = RMR × Activity Factor. This is the most validated equation for general populations.
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="accord">
      <button class="accord-hdr" onclick="tog(this)">Macronutrient Targets by Goal — Reference Table <svg width="16" height="16" viewBox="0 0 24 24" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2"><polyline points="6 9 12 15 18 9"/></svg></button>
      <div class="accord-body">
        <table class="drill-table" style="margin-top:0.5rem;">
          <tr><th>Goal</th><th>Protein</th><th>Carbs</th><th>Fat</th><th>Calorie Adjust</th></tr>
          <tr><td><strong>Fat Loss</strong></td><td>1.6–2.2 g/kg</td><td>3–5 g/kg</td><td>0.8–1.2 g/kg</td><td>−300–500 kcal below TDEE</td></tr>
          <tr><td><strong>Maintenance/Recomp</strong></td><td>1.6–2.0 g/kg</td><td>4–6 g/kg</td><td>1.0–1.5 g/kg</td><td>At TDEE</td></tr>
          <tr><td><strong>Muscle Gain</strong></td><td>1.6–2.2 g/kg</td><td>5–7 g/kg</td><td>1.0–1.5 g/kg</td><td>+200–400 kcal above TDEE</td></tr>
          <tr><td><strong>GLP-1/AOM</strong></td><td>1.8–2.4 g/kg</td><td>3–4 g/kg</td><td>0.8–1.0 g/kg</td><td>Varies — may be 1,000–1,400 kcal</td></tr>
          <tr><td><strong>Older Adults 55+</strong></td><td>1.6–2.0 g/kg</td><td>4–5 g/kg</td><td>1.0–1.3 g/kg</td><td>At TDEE or slight deficit</td></tr>
        </table>
        <br><em>1 g protein = 4 kcal · 1 g carbohydrate = 4 kcal · 1 g fat = 9 kcal</em>
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="cards-grid">
      <div class="ref-card"><div class="ref-card-label">Pre-Workout Timing</div><h3>Fueling Before Training</h3><ul><li><strong>1–3 hours before:</strong> Carbs 1–4 g/kg + Protein 20–40g + Low fat</li><li><strong>30–60 min before:</strong> Small carb snack if needed (banana, rice cake)</li><li><strong>Examples:</strong> Oats + whey, rice + chicken, banana + PB</li></ul></div>
      <div class="ref-card"><div class="ref-card-label">Post-Workout Timing</div><h3>Recovery Nutrition</h3><ul><li><strong>Within 30–60 min:</strong> 20–40g protein + 0.5–1.5 g/kg carbs</li><li><strong>Low fat</strong> immediately post-exercise (slows digestion)</li><li><strong>Examples:</strong> Whey + banana, Greek yogurt + fruit, chocolate milk</li></ul></div>
      <div class="ref-card"><div class="ref-card-label">Hydration</div><h3>Daily & Exercise Targets</h3><ul><li><strong>Baseline:</strong> 35–45 ml/kg body weight daily</li><li><strong>Pre-exercise:</strong> 400–600 ml (2 hrs before)</li><li><strong>During:</strong> 150–250 ml every 15–20 min</li><li><strong>Post:</strong> 500 ml per lb sweat lost</li><li><strong>Electrolytes:</strong> Required for sessions &gt;60 min</li></ul></div>
    </div>
  </div>
</div>

<!-- ══ OPT MODEL ══ -->
<div class="panel" data-panel="opt">
  <div class="ref-panel">
    <div class="ref-header"><h2>NASM OPT Model</h2><p>Optimum Performance Training — the foundational periodization framework. Determine client phase, then prescribe appropriate volume, intensity, and progression. Always progress through phases in sequence.</p></div>
    <div class="phase-row">
      <div class="phase-card"><div class="phase-num">1</div><div class="phase-name">Stabilization Endurance</div><div class="phase-detail"><strong>Sets:</strong> 1–3 &nbsp;|&nbsp; <strong>Reps:</strong> 12–20<br><strong>Intensity:</strong> 50–70% 1RM<br><strong>Tempo:</strong> 4-2-1<br><strong>Rest:</strong> 0–90 sec<br><strong>Duration:</strong> 4 weeks<br><br>Proprioception, joint stability, neuromuscular efficiency. Unstable surfaces, slow tempo. Best for deconditioned, post-rehab, new clients.</div></div>
      <div class="phase-card" style="border-top-color:#60a5fa;"><div class="phase-num" style="color:#60a5fa;">2</div><div class="phase-name">Strength Endurance</div><div class="phase-detail"><strong>Sets:</strong> 2–4 &nbsp;|&nbsp; <strong>Reps:</strong> 8–12<br><strong>Intensity:</strong> 70–80% 1RM<br><strong>Tempo:</strong> 2-0-2<br><strong>Rest:</strong> 0–60 sec<br><strong>Superset:</strong> Strength + Stabilization<br><br>Muscular endurance + strength. Superset strength exercise with stabilization move. Bridge between Phases 1 and 3.</div></div>
      <div class="phase-card" style="border-top-color:var(--green);"><div class="phase-num" style="color:var(--green);">3</div><div class="phase-name">Muscular Development</div><div class="phase-detail"><strong>Sets:</strong> 3–5 &nbsp;|&nbsp; <strong>Reps:</strong> 6–12<br><strong>Intensity:</strong> 75–85% 1RM<br><strong>Tempo:</strong> 2-0-2<br><strong>Rest:</strong> 0–60 sec<br><strong>Duration:</strong> 4+ weeks<br><br>Hypertrophy via mechanical tension, metabolic stress, and muscle damage. High volume, moderate rest.</div></div>
      <div class="phase-card" style="border-top-color:var(--amber);"><div class="phase-num" style="color:var(--amber);">4</div><div class="phase-name">Maximal Strength</div><div class="phase-detail"><strong>Sets:</strong> 4–6 &nbsp;|&nbsp; <strong>Reps:</strong> 1–5<br><strong>Intensity:</strong> 85–100% 1RM<br><strong>Tempo:</strong> Explosive<br><strong>Rest:</strong> 3–5 min<br><br>Maximal motor unit recruitment. Heavy compound lifts. Performance-focused clients. Not typical for general fitness.</div></div>
      <div class="phase-card" style="border-top-color:var(--red);"><div class="phase-num" style="color:var(--red);">5</div><div class="phase-name">Power</div><div class="phase-detail"><strong>Sets:</strong> 3–5 &nbsp;|&nbsp; <strong>Reps:</strong> 1–10<br><strong>Intensity:</strong> 30–45% 1RM (speed-based)<br><strong>Tempo:</strong> Explosive<br><strong>Rest:</strong> 3–5 min<br><br>Rate of force development. Superset heavy strength + explosive power. Athletes and advanced clients only.</div></div>
    </div>
    <div class="accord"><button class="accord-hdr open" onclick="tog(this)">OPT Warm-Up Sequence (All Phases) <svg width="16" height="16" viewBox="0 0 24 24" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2"><polyline points="6 9 12 15 18 9"/></svg></button>
      <div class="accord-body open">
        <span class="sub-lbl">Step 1 — Inhibit (SMR)</span>Foam roll overactive muscles identified in postural assessment. Hold tender spots 30–90 sec.
        <span class="sub-lbl">Step 2 — Lengthen (Static Stretch)</span>Stretch same overactive muscles. Hold 20–30 sec each.
        <span class="sub-lbl">Step 3 — Activate (Isolated Activation)</span>Activate underactive muscles. 1–2 sets × 10–15 reps. Controlled, isolated movements.
        <span class="sub-lbl">Step 4 — Integrate (Dynamic Movement)</span>Multi-joint dynamic exercises reinforcing new movement patterns.
        <span class="sub-lbl">Common Postural Patterns</span>
        <ul><li><strong>Pronation distortion:</strong> Overactive calves/adductors → Underactive glutes/tibialis anterior</li><li><strong>Lower crossed:</strong> Overactive hip flexors/lumbar extensors → Underactive glutes/core</li><li><strong>Upper crossed:</strong> Overactive upper traps/pecs → Underactive mid/lower traps/deep cervical flexors</li></ul>
      </div>
    </div>
    <div class="accord"><button class="accord-hdr" onclick="tog(this)">ACE IFT Model Reference <svg width="16" height="16" viewBox="0 0 24 24" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2"><polyline points="6 9 12 15 18 9"/></svg></button>
      <div class="accord-body">ACE Integrated Fitness Training model — 4 phases. Never advance until client demonstrates competency.
        <span class="sub-lbl">Phase 1 — Stability & Mobility</span>Restore joint mobility/stability. Correct imbalances before loading.
        <span class="sub-lbl">Phase 2 — Movement</span>Build foundational patterns: squat, hinge, push, pull, rotate, locomotion.
        <span class="sub-lbl">Phase 3 — Load</span>Progressive resistance training with external load. Introduce periodization.
        <span class="sub-lbl">Phase 4 — Performance</span>Power, speed, agility, sport-specific. Advanced clients and athletes only.
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>
</div>

<!-- ══ OLYMPIC LIFTING ══ -->
<div class="panel" data-panel="olympic">
  <div class="ref-panel">
    <div class="ref-header"><h2>Olympic Weightlifting</h2><p>Snatch coaching model from EPI Phase 2 NCSC course. Always begin with Phase 1 (bar only). Allow 3–4 sessions per phase before progressing. Olympic lifts produce some of the highest power outputs of any exercise modality — during the second pull of the clean and snatch, an average of 52 W/kg body weight is produced vs. ~12 W/kg in powerlifting.</p></div>

    <div class="accord"><button class="accord-hdr open" onclick="tog(this)">Snatch Set-Up & Key Positions <svg width="16" height="16" viewBox="0 0 24 24" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2"><polyline points="6 9 12 15 18 9"/></svg></button>
      <div class="accord-body open">
        <span class="sub-lbl">Hook Grip</span>Wrap thumb around bar first, then hook index and middle fingers over the thumb.
        <span class="sub-lbl">Grip Width</span>Wide enough so bar sits in lower abdominal region (above pubic symphysis, below ASIS) when arms are straight standing.
        <span class="sub-lbl">Jump Stance (Start)</span>Feet hip-width apart, pointing straight. This is the power position.
        <span class="sub-lbl">Catch Stance</span>Feet shoulder-width apart, turned outward (11 & 1 o'clock positions).
        <span class="sub-lbl">Overhead Position</span>Bar above crown of head, arms locked, face through the bar.
        <span class="sub-lbl">Sit Position (Pre-lift)</span>Slight flex through ankle, knee, hip. Bar in upper thigh. This is the launch position.
        <span class="sub-lbl">Start Position Key Points (from floor)</span>
        <ul><li>Feet hip-width, bar over big toe knuckle, shins close</li><li>Hook grip, wide enough for crease-of-hip bar position when standing</li><li>Hips slightly higher than knees but lower than Clean start</li><li>Shoulders in front of bar, back flat, scapulae retracted, elbows pointing outward</li><li>Weight distribution: mid to forefoot</li></ul>
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="accord"><button class="accord-hdr" onclick="tog(this)">Snatch Coaching Model — Phase 1, 2 & 3 Drills <svg width="16" height="16" viewBox="0 0 24 24" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2"><polyline points="6 9 12 15 18 9"/></svg></button>
      <div class="accord-body">
        <table class="drill-table">
          <tr><th>Phase</th><th>Drill</th><th>Key Points</th><th>Sets/Reps</th></tr>
          <tr><td colspan="4" class="drill-phase-hdr" style="padding:6px 12px;font-size:0.72rem;letter-spacing:0.1em;">PHASE 1 — Crease of Hip Position (Sessions 1–4)</td></tr>
          <tr><td>1</td><td><strong>Shrug & Triple Extend</strong></td><td>Begin in sit position, jump stance. Triple extend ankle/knee/hip whilst shrugging. Focus on hip drive — not arm pull.</td><td>3×6, 30s rest, bar only</td></tr>
          <tr><td>2</td><td><strong>Elbows High</strong></td><td>Same as above + simultaneously drive hips and pull bar. Elbows high throughout.</td><td>3×6, 30s rest, bar only</td></tr>
          <tr><td>3</td><td><strong>Muscle Snatch</strong></td><td>Triple extend + pull + receive bar overhead with legs straight.</td><td>3×6, 30s rest, bar only</td></tr>
          <tr><td>4</td><td><strong>Overhead Squat</strong></td><td>Bar overhead, catch stance. Lower into deep squat, drive knees out over toes, maintain upright torso.</td><td>3×6, 30s rest, bar only</td></tr>
          <tr><td>5</td><td><strong>Snatch Land</strong></td><td>From overhead position, drop and land in quarter squat. Feet shift jump → catch stance.</td><td>3×6, 30s rest, bar only</td></tr>
          <tr><td>6</td><td><strong>Snatch Drop</strong></td><td>Same as land but receive in deep squat position.</td><td>3×6, 30s rest, bar only</td></tr>
          <tr><td>7</td><td><strong>Jump & Catch</strong></td><td>From sit position, triple extend + pull, drop and catch bar overhead. Full integration of Phase 1.</td><td>3×6 + 1×4 circuit, bar only</td></tr>
          <tr><td colspan="4" class="drill-phase-hdr" style="padding:6px 12px;font-size:0.72rem;letter-spacing:0.1em;">PHASE 2 — Hang Position / Mid-Thigh (Sessions 5–8)</td></tr>
          <tr><td>1</td><td><strong>Hang Slides</strong></td><td>From sit position, slide bar down front of thighs to mid-lower thigh. Keep shoulders in front of bar. Stand to repeat.</td><td>3×6, 30s rest, bar only</td></tr>
          <tr><td>2</td><td><strong>Hang Shrug & Triple Extend</strong></td><td>From hang position: triple extend + shrug. Focus on hip drive.</td><td>3×6, 30s rest, bar only</td></tr>
          <tr><td>3</td><td><strong>Muscle Snatch (Hang)</strong></td><td>From hang: triple extend + pull + receive overhead with legs straight.</td><td>3×6, 30s rest, bar only</td></tr>
          <tr><td>4</td><td><strong>Hang Snatch</strong></td><td>From mid-lower thigh: triple extend + pull, drop and catch bar overhead in catch stance. Full hang version.</td><td>3×6 + 1×4 circuit, bar only</td></tr>
          <tr><td colspan="4" class="drill-phase-hdr" style="padding:6px 12px;font-size:0.72rem;letter-spacing:0.1em;">PHASE 3 — Floor Position (Sessions 9–12)</td></tr>
          <tr><td>1</td><td><strong>Snatch Pull</strong></td><td>Bar at mid-shin, jump stance. Rise hips and shoulders at same rate (clear the knee). Contact hip at crease by triple extending + shrugging simultaneously.</td><td>3×6, 30s rest, bar only</td></tr>
          <tr><td>2</td><td><strong>Power Snatch</strong></td><td>Full lift from floor. Receive bar overhead in quarter squat, catch stance. First loaded progression.</td><td>3×6, 30s rest, bar only</td></tr>
          <tr><td>3</td><td><strong>Squat Snatch</strong></td><td>Full lift from floor. Receive bar overhead in deep squat, catch stance. Full technical snatch.</td><td>3×6 + 1×4 circuit, bar only</td></tr>
        </table>
        <br><strong>Supplementary Drills:</strong> Sott's Press (overhead squat with press), Snatch Balance (drop + press overhead from behind neck).
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="accord"><button class="accord-hdr" onclick="tog(this)">Snatch Technical Model — Common Errors & Cues <svg width="16" height="16" viewBox="0 0 24 24" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2"><polyline points="6 9 12 15 18 9"/></svg></button>
      <div class="accord-body">
        <table class="drill-table">
          <tr><th>Error</th><th>Coaching Cue</th><th>Root Cause</th></tr>
          <tr><td colspan="3" class="drill-phase-hdr" style="padding:6px 12px;font-size:0.72rem;letter-spacing:0.1em;">START POSITION ERRORS</td></tr>
          <tr><td><strong>Rounded back</strong></td><td>"Back straight" / "Spread the chest"</td><td>Lack of T-spine extension / hip anterior pelvic tilt mobility</td></tr>
          <tr><td><strong>Hips too high</strong></td><td>"Hips down — chest up" / "Show me your logo"</td><td>Lack of ankle dorsiflexion / hip extension mobility</td></tr>
          <tr><td colspan="3" class="drill-phase-hdr" style="padding:6px 12px;font-size:0.72rem;letter-spacing:0.1em;">FIRST PULL ERRORS</td></tr>
          <tr><td><strong>Butt shoot (hips rise faster than shoulders)</strong></td><td>"Stay tall" / "Chest up"</td><td>Athlete pulling bar too fast from floor — first pull should be slow and controlled</td></tr>
