<!-- ══ RECOVERY METHODS ══ -->
<div class="panel" data-panel="recovery">
  <div class="ref-panel">
    <div class="ref-header"><h2>Recovery Methods</h2><p>Evidence-based recovery modalities from EPI Phase 2. Adequate recovery restores physiological and psychological processes so athletes can train or compete at the required level. Mechanical stress (sprinting, lifting) and metabolic stress (endurance) require different recovery approaches.</p></div>
    <div class="cards-grid">
      <div class="ref-card"><div class="ref-card-label">Hydrotherapy</div><h3>Cold Water Immersion (CWI)</h3><span class="tag tag-g">Strong Evidence</span><ul><li><strong>Protocol:</strong> 1 × 5 min @ 10°C (50°F)</li><li>Immersion depth: waist to shoulder</li><li>Reduces DOMS, speeds muscle function recovery</li><li>Outperforms hot water immersion and passive recovery for sprint and time trial performance</li></ul></div>
      <div class="ref-card"><div class="ref-card-label">Hydrotherapy</div><h3>Contrast Water Therapy (CWT)</h3><span class="tag tag-g">Strong Evidence</span><ul><li><strong>Protocol:</strong> 4 min @ 40°C + 2 min @ 10°C × 2 rounds (always finish cold)</li><li>Alternates hot and cold immersion to create "pump" effect</li><li>Comparable to CWI for performance recovery</li><li>Most popular in elite sports settings</li></ul></div>
      <div class="ref-card"><div class="ref-card-label">Active Recovery</div><h3>Low-Intensity Active Recovery</h3><span class="tag tag-b">Moderate Evidence</span><ul><li><strong>Protocol:</strong> Stationary bike 1 × 15 min @ 50–60% MaxHR</li><li>Most common recovery method used by athletes</li><li>Role in lactate clearance — evidence incomplete but anecdotally effective</li><li>No detrimental effects vs. passive recovery</li></ul></div>
      <div class="ref-card"><div class="ref-card-label">Compression</div><h3>Compression Garments</h3><span class="tag tag-b">Moderate Evidence</span><ul><li><strong>Protocol:</strong> Wear immediately after training for remainder of day</li><li>Improves venous return via graduated compression (proximal → distal)</li><li>Moderate benefit: reduces muscle soreness and CK levels</li><li>Improves recovery of muscle strength and power</li></ul></div>
      <div class="ref-card"><div class="ref-card-label">Manual Therapy</div><h3>Massage</h3><span class="tag tag-r">Limited Performance Evidence</span><ul><li>Beneficial for <strong>psychological</strong> recovery and perceived soreness</li><li>Limited evidence for improving functional performance recovery</li><li>Valuable for injury prevention — improves muscle tone and resting length</li><li>Should be included in programs for reasons beyond recovery</li></ul></div>
      <div class="ref-card"><div class="ref-card-label">Flexibility</div><h3>Stretching</h3><span class="tag tag-r">Inconclusive Evidence</span><ul><li>Research is mixed — not conclusively effective as recovery modality</li><li>Some studies show improved power output 15 hrs post-match</li><li>Others show no benefit vs. CWT or active recovery</li><li>Implement case-by-case — if client feels it helps, allow it</li></ul></div>
    </div>
    <div class="accord"><button class="accord-hdr open" onclick="tog(this)">Recovery Method Hierarchy — Evidence Summary <svg width="16" height="16" viewBox="0 0 24 24" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2"><polyline points="6 9 12 15 18 9"/></svg></button>
      <div class="accord-body open">
        <strong>Ranked by evidence for performance recovery:</strong>
        <ul>
          <li><strong>1. CWI / CWT (Hydrotherapy):</strong> Strongest evidence for reducing DOMS and improving next-day performance. CWT slightly preferred by athletes. Use post-high-intensity or competition days.</li>
          <li><strong>2. Active Recovery:</strong> Most widely used. No harm, some benefit. Best for metabolic stress recovery (high-intensity cardio/conditioning).</li>
          <li><strong>3. Compression Garments:</strong> Moderate evidence. Practical and passive — good for travel or post-session without access to pools.</li>
          <li><strong>4. Massage:</strong> Psychological benefit is real. Physical performance benefit is limited. Still valuable for muscle tone and injury prevention.</li>
          <li><strong>5. Stretching:</strong> Trainer and athlete preference. Implement case-by-case. Not harmful. May have minor post-match benefit.</li>
        </ul>
        <span class="sub-lbl">Sleep — The Overlooked Priority</span>
        Sleep is the most powerful recovery intervention and often the most neglected. 7–9 hours of quality sleep per night is the foundation all other modalities build on. Prioritize sleep education with every client before implementing recovery modalities.
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>
</div>

<!-- ══ STRENGTH & POWER ══ -->
<div class="panel" data-panel="strength">
  <div class="ref-panel">
    <div class="ref-header"><h2>Strength & Power</h2><p>EPI Phase 2 Strength & Power content — neuromuscular system, hypertrophy mechanisms, force-velocity curve, and training methods. Strength (Force = Mass × Acceleration) is the prerequisite for Power (Force × Velocity).</p></div>
    <div class="cards-grid">
      <div class="ref-card"><div class="ref-card-label">Neuromuscular</div><h3>Motor Unit Recruitment</h3><ul><li><strong>Size Principle:</strong> CNS recruits smallest (Type I) units first, progresses to larger (Type II) as force demands increase</li><li>Jogging = low threshold Type I recruitment; Sprinting = high threshold Type II</li><li>Two factors determining muscle recruitment: <strong>level of force</strong> and <strong>rate of force development (RFD)</strong></li><li>Lifting lighter loads fast recruits most motor units at loads as low as 33% 1RM</li></ul></div>
      <div class="ref-card"><div class="ref-card-label">Neuromuscular</div><h3>Rate Coding & Synchronisation</h3><ul><li><strong>Rate Coding:</strong> Increasing frequency of neural impulses to already-recruited motor units — force increases without additional recruitment</li><li>Explosive exercises (Olympic lifts) increase rate coding of higher-threshold motor units</li><li><strong>Motor Unit Synchronisation:</strong> Simultaneous activation of 2+ motor units — more related to RFD</li><li>Heavy strength training may increase synchronisation, contributing to force production</li></ul></div>
      <div class="ref-card"><div class="ref-card-label">Muscle Fiber Types</div><h3>Type I vs Type II</h3><ul><li><strong>Type I (Slow Twitch):</strong> Fatigue resistant, peak tension ~110ms, oxidative fuel, endurance</li><li><strong>Type II (Fast Twitch):</strong> Peak tension ~50ms, glycolytic, strength and power, fatigues quickly</li><li>Type IIa = intermediate; Type IIx = most powerful, most fatigable</li><li>Average human: ~equal Type I and II, with large interindividual variability</li></ul></div>
      <div class="ref-card"><div class="ref-card-label">Hypertrophy</div><h3>3 Mechanisms of Muscle Growth</h3><ul><li><strong>1. Mechanical Tension:</strong> Primary driver — load applied to muscle stimulates mTOR signalling and protein synthesis</li><li><strong>2. Metabolic Stress:</strong> "The pump" — lactate/H+ accumulation causes cell swelling, hormonal response, anabolic signalling</li><li><strong>3. Muscle Damage (EIMD):</strong> Eccentric actions cause most damage — structural changes drive adaptation and hypertrophy</li></ul></div>
      <div class="ref-card"><div class="ref-card-label">Hypertrophy Techniques</div><h3>Advanced Training Methods</h3><ul><li><strong>Cluster Sets:</strong> Short intraset rests (10–30s) between mini-reps — better mechanical tension, less metabolic stress. Best for functional hypertrophy.</li><li><strong>Supersets:</strong> Two exercises back-to-back. Can target same or opposing muscle groups. Increases metabolic stress + volume.</li><li><strong>Drop Sets:</strong> Reduce load ~10% immediately at fatigue and continue. High metabolic stress.</li><li><strong>Pre-Exhaustion:</strong> Isolation exercise first to pre-fatigue agonist before compound lift. Maximizes metabolic stress on target muscle.</li></ul></div>
      <div class="ref-card"><div class="ref-card-label">Power Development</div><h3>Complex Training & PAP</h3><ul><li><strong>Complex Training:</strong> Pair heavy loaded exercise with biomechanically similar plyometric exercise in same set</li><li><strong>Post-Activation Potentiation (PAP):</strong> Prior heavy contraction enhances explosive capability — neural excitability + myosin phosphorylation</li><li><strong>Intracomplex rest:</strong> 1–4 minutes between loaded and plyometric exercise</li><li>Requires: &gt;2 years RT, &gt;1.8 relative 1RM lower body, &gt;1.4 relative 1RM upper body</li><li><strong>Example:</strong> Back Squat 3×3 @ 90% → (rest 1–2 min) → CMJ 3×4</li></ul></div>
    </div>
    <div class="accord"><button class="accord-hdr open" onclick="tog(this)">Force-Velocity Curve & Programming Roadmap <svg width="16" height="16" viewBox="0 0 24 24" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2"><polyline points="6 9 12 15 18 9"/></svg></button>
      <div class="accord-body open">
        The FV curve is the S&C coach's roadmap. Maximum strength is expressed at low velocities; maximum speed at low loads. An inverse relationship exists between force and velocity.
        <span class="sub-lbl">FV Zones</span>
        <table class="drill-table" style="margin-top:0.5rem;">
          <tr><th>Zone</th><th>Load</th><th>Method</th></tr>
          <tr><td><strong>Max Strength</strong></td><td>90–100% 1RM</td><td>Heavy compound lifts (Back Squat, Deadlift, Bench Press) — 1–5 reps</td></tr>
          <tr><td><strong>Strength-Speed</strong></td><td>80–90% 1RM</td><td>Olympic lifts (Squat Clean, Squat Snatch, Clean/Snatch Pull) — 1–3 reps</td></tr>
          <tr><td><strong>Peak Power</strong></td><td>30–80% 1RM</td><td>Power Clean, Power Snatch, Loaded Squat Jumps — 1–4 reps</td></tr>
          <tr><td><strong>Speed-Strength</strong></td><td>30–60% 1RM</td><td>Hang Clean, Hang Snatch, Plyometrics — 3–4 reps</td></tr>
          <tr><td><strong>Max Speed</strong></td><td>&lt;30% 1RM</td><td>Reactive plyometrics: pogos, depth jumps, rebound hurdles — 1–6 reps</td></tr>
        </table>
        <span class="sub-lbl">Programming Principle</span>
        Develop all areas of the FV curve across the training cycle. Initially build max strength, then exploit those adaptations through explosive/ballistic work. Strength training must be maintained throughout (reduced frequency in-season). The <strong>intent to move explosively</strong> is critical at any load.
        <span class="sub-lbl">Ballistic Training & RFD</span>
        Most athletic movements occur in &lt;0.3 seconds. Train RFD by lifting lighter loads at maximal velocity intent, plyometrics, and Olympic lifts. Olympic lifts produce ~52 W/kg vs. ~12 W/kg in powerlifting during equivalent phases.
      </div>
    </div>
    <div class="accord"><button class="accord-hdr" onclick="tog(this)">Variable Resistance Training (Bands & Chains) <svg width="16" height="16" viewBox="0 0 24 24" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2"><polyline points="6 9 12 15 18 9"/></svg></button>
      <div class="accord-body">
        Variable resistance training alters external resistance through the range of motion to maximize muscle force production at all joint angles.
        <span class="sub-lbl">Band Set-Up</span>
        <ul><li>Anchor to stable surfaces (squat rack pegs, heavy dumbbells, bench)</li><li>Bands must never go slack during any portion of the lift</li><li>Keep bands vertically oriented to the floor</li></ul>
        <span class="sub-lbl">Chain Set-Up</span>
        <ul><li>Use lighter lead chain to attach heavy chains to barbell</li><li>Hang heavy chain doubled over lead chain from midline (not end to end)</li><li>Heavy chain must remain in contact with floor at all times</li><li>Some links must stay grounded at the top of the range</li></ul>
        <strong>Purpose:</strong> Induces varied stimuli → neural adaptations improving strength and power. Bands also increase eccentric stimulus during the lowering phase.
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>
</div>

<!-- ══ INJURY GUIDE ══ -->
<div class="panel" data-panel="injury">
  <div class="ref-panel">
    <div class="ref-header"><h2>Injury Modification Guide</h2><p>Exercise modifications for common client complaints. Trainers modify — not diagnose. Always advise clients to consult a physician or PT for diagnosis.</p></div>
    <div class="alert-box"><svg width="16" height="16" viewBox="0 0 24 24" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2" style="flex-shrink:0;margin-top:1px;"><path d="M10.29 3.86L1.82 18a2 2 0 001.71 3h16.94a2 2 0 001.71-3L13.71 3.86a2 2 0 00-3.42 0z"/><line x1="12" y1="9" x2="12" y2="13"/><line x1="12" y1="17" x2="12.01" y2="17"/></svg><span><strong>Scope of practice:</strong> Stop training and advise physician/PT consult if client reports sharp, radiating, sudden-onset, or worsening pain.</span></div>
    <div class="cards-grid">
      <div class="ref-card"><div class="ref-card-label">Lower Body</div><h3>Knee Pain / Anterior Knee</h3><span class="tag tag-r">Avoid</span>Deep knee flexion past 90°, plyometrics, forward-knee lunges<br><br><span class="tag tag-g">Modify To</span><ul><li>Box squat (controlled depth, sit back)</li><li>Leg press (foot position high)</li><li>Seated leg extension (pain-free arc)</li><li>Step-ups (6–8 inch box)</li><li>Romanian deadlift / hip hinge</li><li>Lying or seated hamstring curls</li></ul></div>
      <div class="ref-card"><div class="ref-card-label">Lower Body</div><h3>Low Back Pain</h3><span class="tag tag-r">Avoid</span>Loaded spinal flexion, heavy deadlifts, sit-ups, good mornings<br><br><span class="tag tag-g">Modify To</span><ul><li>Bird dog (core anti-extension)</li><li>Dead bug progressions</li><li>Glute bridges / hip thrusts</li><li>Pallof press (anti-rotation)</li><li>Cable pull-throughs</li><li>Trap bar deadlift if pain-free</li></ul></div>
      <div class="ref-card"><div class="ref-card-label">Upper Body</div><h3>Shoulder Impingement</h3><span class="tag tag-r">Avoid</span>Overhead press, upright rows, behind-neck movements, internal rotation under load<br><br><span class="tag tag-g">Modify To</span><ul><li>Landmine press</li><li>Cable face pulls</li><li>Band external rotation</li><li>Neutral-grip DB press</li><li>Seated cable row (horizontal)</li><li>Scapular pushups</li></ul></div>
      <div class="ref-card"><div class="ref-card-label">Lower Body</div><h3>Plantar Fasciitis</h3><span class="tag tag-r">Avoid</span>Running, jumping, high-impact cardio, prolonged standing on hard surfaces<br><br><span class="tag tag-g">Modify To</span><ul><li>Seated stationary bike</li><li>Swimming / aqua walking</li><li>Upper body or seated resistance</li><li>Foot rolling pre-session</li><li>Calf stretching 3×30s each session</li></ul></div>
      <div class="ref-card"><div class="ref-card-label">Upper Body</div><h3>Tennis / Golfer's Elbow</h3><span class="tag tag-r">Avoid</span>Barbell curls supinated, heavy gripping, wrist curls<br><br><span class="tag tag-g">Modify To</span><ul><li>Neutral/hammer curls</li><li>TRX rows (reduced grip)</li><li>Machine-based pulling</li><li>Wrist flexor/extensor stretches</li><li>Eccentric wrist exercises</li></ul></div>
      <div class="ref-card"><div class="ref-card-label">Core / Hip</div><h3>Hip Flexor Strain</h3><span class="tag tag-r">Avoid</span>Sprinting, high-knee drills, hanging leg raises<br><br><span class="tag tag-g">Modify To</span><ul><li>Glute bridges (hip extension focus)</li><li>Prone hip extensions</li><li>Side-lying clamshells</li><li>Short-stride walking lunges</li><li>Stationary bike (low resistance)</li></ul></div>
    </div>
    <div class="accord"><button class="accord-hdr" onclick="tog(this)">Red Flag Symptoms — Stop & Refer Immediately <svg width="16" height="16" viewBox="0 0 24 24" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2"><polyline points="6 9 12 15 18 9"/></svg></button>
      <div class="accord-body">Stop the session. If cardiac symptoms are present, call 911. Notify the Fitness Director. Document the incident.<ul><li><strong>Chest pain, pressure, or tightness</strong> during or after exercise</li><li><strong>Pain radiating</strong> down the arm, leg, or into the jaw</li><li><strong>Sudden dizziness, loss of balance, or fainting</strong></li><li><strong>Acute joint swelling</strong> appearing during activity</li><li><strong>Numbness or tingling</strong> in any extremity</li><li><strong>Severe shortness of breath</strong> disproportionate to effort</li><li><strong>Sharp, stabbing pain</strong> that doesn't resolve with rest</li><li>Pain rated <strong>7/10 or higher</strong></li></ul>
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>
</div>

<!-- ══ NUTRITION ══ -->
<div class="panel" data-panel="nutrition">
  <div class="ref-panel">
    <div class="ref-header"><h2>Nutrition Reference</h2><p>Evidence-based nutrition guidance. Trainers provide general education — refer detailed dietary planning to a Registered Dietitian. Use the Calorie & Macro Calculator tab for client-specific estimates.</p></div>
    <div class="cards-grid">
      <div class="ref-card"><div class="ref-card-label">Fat Loss</div><h3>Weight Loss Macros</h3><ul><li><strong>Protein:</strong> 1.6–2.2 g/kg BW</li><li><strong>Carbs:</strong> 3–5 g/kg</li><li><strong>Fat:</strong> 0.8–1.2 g/kg</li><li><strong>Deficit:</strong> 300–500 kcal below TDEE</li><li><strong>Key:</strong> Protein is top priority — preserves lean mass in deficit</li></ul></div>
      <div class="ref-card"><div class="ref-card-label">Muscle Gain</div><h3>Hypertrophy Macros</h3><ul><li><strong>Protein:</strong> 1.6–2.2 g/kg BW</li><li><strong>Carbs:</strong> 5–7 g/kg</li><li><strong>Fat:</strong> 1.0–1.5 g/kg</li><li><strong>Surplus:</strong> 200–400 kcal above TDEE</li><li><strong>Key:</strong> Carb timing around training windows matters</li></ul></div>
      <div class="ref-card"><div class="ref-card-label">Supplements</div><h3>Evidence-Based Only</h3><ul><li><strong>Creatine monohydrate:</strong> 3–5g/day — strength, power, recovery</li><li><strong>Whey protein:</strong> Complete, fast-digesting source</li><li><strong>Caffeine:</strong> 3–6 mg/kg, 30–60 min pre-exercise</li><li><strong>Vitamin D3:</strong> 1,000–2,000 IU/day (especially indoor athletes)</li><li><strong>Omega-3:</strong> 1–3g/day — anti-inflammatory, joint support</li><li><strong>Magnesium:</strong> 300–400mg/day — sleep, muscle recovery</li></ul></div>
    </div>
    <div class="accord"><button class="accord-hdr open" onclick="tog(this)">GLP-1 / AOM Client Nutrition Protocols <svg width="16" height="16" viewBox="0 0 24 24" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2"><polyline points="6 9 12 15 18 9"/></svg></button>
      <div class="accord-body open">
        <span class="sub-lbl">The Core Problem</span>Without adequate resistance training and protein, <strong>25–40% of weight lost on GLP-1 medications is lean muscle mass.</strong> Protein intake is the nutritional intervention.
        <span class="sub-lbl">Protein Priority</span><ul><li>Target <strong>1.8–2.4 g/kg</strong> BW — higher due to appetite suppression and anabolic resistance</li><li>Distribute across 4–5 small meals — large meals often not tolerable</li><li><strong>Protein-first eating</strong> at every meal</li><li>Whey or casein shakes when appetite too low to hit targets from food</li></ul>
        <span class="sub-lbl">Trainer's Actions</span><ul><li>Reinforce resistance training as non-negotiable</li><li>Educate on protein targets at every session</li><li>Adjust training intensity on high-nausea/low-energy days</li><li>Refer to RD for meal planning</li></ul>
      </div>
    </div>
    <div class="accord"><button class="accord-hdr" onclick="tog(this)">Older Adult Nutrition (55+) <svg width="16" height="16" viewBox="0 0 24 24" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2"><polyline points="6 9 12 15 18 9"/></svg></button>
      <div class="accord-body">
        <span class="sub-lbl">Protein — Higher Needs Due to Anabolic Resistance</span><ul><li>Target <strong>1.6–2.0 g/kg</strong> BW — need more than younger adults for same MPS response</li><li>Minimum <strong>30–40g per meal</strong> to maximally stimulate MPS</li><li>Leucine-rich sources: eggs, dairy, poultry, fish, legumes</li></ul>
        <span class="sub-lbl">Key Micronutrients</span><ul><li><strong>Calcium:</strong> 1,200 mg/day (women 51+), 1,000 mg (men 51+)</li><li><strong>Vitamin D:</strong> 800–2,000 IU/day</li><li><strong>B12:</strong> Absorption decreases with age — supplementation often necessary</li></ul>
